snippet.textDisplay:
I picked OnePlus 7T, Huawei Mate 30 Pro, Samsung Note 10+, LG G8X, Samsung S10e, iPhone 11 Pro, Google Pixel 4, and Huawei P30 Pro for round one.

I picked OnePlus 7T, Samsung Note 10+, iPhone 11 Pro, and Google Pixel 4 for round two.

I picked OnePlus 7T and iPhone 11 Pro for the finals. It would have been difficult if the bracket was arranged with the Pixel 4 opposite the iPhone, but the iPhone easily outdoes the OnePlus 7T Pro so obviously it’ll beat the regular 7T.

In my mind, this award belongs to either the OnePlus 7T Pro, iPhone 11 Pro, or Google Pixel 4. Those all have amazing cameras! I’m very disappointed to see Samsung win this one... if you look at the photos and the votes that went along with them, there are some surprisingly inferior photos winning their respective matches! Contrast is important, but some way overdo it and end up looking underexposed. Others won being totally washed out, too! But to be fair, I can tell a Samsung photo when I see one so I know people who use those phones can too, so “blind” may not be entirely true. Hopefully next year a real phone camera can win... aka OnePlus, Apple, or Google.

snippet.textDisplay: A couple of points: nobody knows what is the most "accurate" reproduction of a scene, because no one was there to witness it. There was also missing selfie photos (although I know it is with a different lens) and night shots (e.g., a party and/or outdoors with bad lighting), which could scramble everything as well. One suggestion is not to have an elimination competition with brackets, but to keep all phones until the end. You could randomised each two photos to show at the same time and the most voted would win one point (changing pairs for each new subject) - at the end, the camera with the most points wins the competition. I believe it would be fairer, because it would remove some flukes, while keeping the competition until the end.

snippet.textDisplay:
About the seeming preference for sharper backgrounds, blurred backgrounds are only good when there's nothing to look at back there and you desire subject separation for artistic reasons.

That green chair pops. That color chart pops. Your shoes pop against the gray ground. These are reasons to have the eye look at those things and reasons people may have voted for sharpness. My takeaway was that people were voting that your composition was asking for a higher f stop than whatever the losing phone was able to provide.

snippet.textDisplay: As someone that totally appreciates what professional tech reviewers do, and DxOMark etc for professional camera reviews, I still think these results are important. Professional reviews and professional opinions are very important, but how the target audience perceives the results (photographs in this case) is also extremely important. You see this all of the time in the automotive industry, where vehicles like the Corolla may not be the best performers in the class but still sell by the boat load every year...it's perception just like here. With a combines 6 million votes PLUS a blind test, it's almost impossible that this was a biased survey. In fact, the vast majority of surveys don't have a sample size this large. So while the Samsung sensor might not be the very best in alot of tech reviewer's opinion, the vast majority of the people that would ostensibly buy one think it's exceptional. Oh, and the Note 10+ currently enjoys a score of 117 on DxOMark's rankings, putting it on the same level as the 11 Pro, 5 points ahead of the Pixel 4, and 4 points behind the Mate 30 Pro...so overall I don't think the results are that surprising.
